Such an amazing sushi/Japanese restaurant! Their hand rolls (Temaki) are interesting, and the heritage pork "Betty" appetizer is phenomenal (get the egg!) Very tasty miso soup. Small menu but they do practically everything well. I don't I've ever ordered anything "meh" from here and I've dined here about 20 times in the past five years. Repeat foodie customer: says it all. I get the hand rolls (one of each: ebi, spicy scallop, and spicy tuna) every time I go. The soy sauce flight they offer is an awesome touch and essential to the meal. I drown my Temaki (hand rolls) in the spicy sauce. I like their sushi bombs but usually I will get one of their specials - the main menu itself has been updated many times. They offer things like fried chicken and turkey leg randomly. This restaurant really hits the spot. It's not luxurious (because someone will complain about the benches and proximity to other diners during peak hours - it's not that bad, or just go during off hours if you're bothered by that sort of thing) but the service is usually superb and you will get a solid meal here. Good place to take a first date if you are feeling nervous and want to break the ice, but not very romantic. Not a place to bring your kids but most places in Bushwick aren't... Yeah, this place is definitely good. I looked over my own review and now I'm hungry!

We dined at the restaurant by chance and it was decent but would not recommend it if you are a bit picky about asian food. We had chicken shoyu ramen, pork mazemen and uni mazemen, phili roll (salmon and tofu cream cheese) karaage and handmade gyoza.  Mazemen were pretty decent but do not get the shoyu ramen. The broth is a bit salty and it just taste like boiled water with soy sauce and slight brothy taste to it. I'm not sure how other ramen are but broth is the life of ramen. And if it's it's anything similar, I would advise against getting it and recommend getting mazemen instead.  The Phili roll had a weird texture to it. Maybe it was the tofu cream cheese but it had this mushy feel to it that made it a bit weird to chew. Gyoza was not bad but nothing to praise about either.

Service wasn't that great...  Spicy Mc Bomb ($7)- 5/5 This one is my favorite sushi bomb out of all of them. The katafi makes such a huge difference- it adds such great texture and gives it a crunch.  Guacamole Tuna- ($8)-4/5 This was pretty small... 6 small little pieces and some that seem to have nonexistent avocado/guacamole? Anyways, it did taste pretty good. The flavor sort of reminds me of tacos but with tuna.  Handmade Vegan Gyoza ($9)-3/5 These were pretty to look at and that's about it. The taste was very average, and definitely not worth $9. It came with some sauces on the side as well.  Ebi ($6)-4/5 This wasn't too memorable, but I remember tasting the cashew. Still pretty good though. It's also quite pricey for a hand roll.  Spicy Tuna ($5)- 4/5 Again, this was another hand roll, and also not that memorable. However, it's still good, but pricey.  Oyako ($9)- 3/5 Very average sushi with roasted salmon, quite "boring" compared to other places. And extremely pricey for the portion..

A very over-priced Japanese food joint. I was very enthusiastic about going to this place as they had a "miso black cod" dish on the menu. Little that I know that what one gets, for $17, is a small piece of fish (smallish appetizer sized, about 3-4 ounces) on a bed of lettuce. Yes, it was fairly tasty, but it should have been described as an appetizer, and not as a "fish dish", and cost half the cost (I did have plenty chances to try this dish on the West Coast, so I know how it should be). The rest of the menu items were also on a smaller size, and we did get somewhat different items than ordered.  In any case, after spending over $60 on lunch for two people, we ended up going elsewhere to get more food as we were still hungry. Compared with far more satisfied Japanese food experience in multiple places in the East Village, this place was extremely disappointing.

Momo is a reflection of what I want this neighborhood to be. Phil's presence gives the outstanding food a human quality, compared to restaurants in the 2-block radius that are so mechanistic (you know who you are).  Anyway, back to Momo - such a superb sushi restaurant, I just can't eat regular sushi anymore. Everything from the diverse and bountiful menu options, to the quality of fish, and best of all, the service. Phil's team of servers are veterans, and most have been there since it opened. It's a true neighborhood spot, that know and love its locals, and care to give tourists and city-goers a taste of the local feel.  As such, it's always a good vibe, especially when Phil is there chatting everyone up. Good people, just absolutely good people there, so be nice to them, and tip them well!

If you're looking for good sushi, pass by this place. Canned tuna is NOT okay. $ 6.50 for a tiny hand roll with canned tuna is a joke. The bombs are decent, nothing special; but they're very expensive for no apparent reason. 7 -8 $ for 3 pieces the size of a water bottle cap. The sushi rolls are plain and very small for triple the price of any normal sushi restaurant. We ordered the karrage( fried chicken ) and it was very disappointing. Chicken tastes like it was a week old, hard and dry, without much flavor. You pay for a hipster atmosphere with a dark room with extremely loud music, a community styled seating. ( elbow to elbow with strangers ) I love good food, and this place does not provide.
Amazing sushi! A bit loud when busy in the evening, but still cozy. Over the top welcoming and caring owner.
Hidden gem of AMAZING modern take on Japanese cuisine

The first time I visited this place, a gentleman at the table next to me had some kind of epileptic seizure. After the seizure, he continued to eat the food he had ordered. That is how good it was. Also: cool shack!

THIS IS AN HONEST REVIEW: Im not a man-ban wearing hipster that is impressed by fad and fashion. When i go out to eat I do so to eat good food. So the truth will hurt.  The good:  Their hamachi was great. The bombs are good. The sake is good.  The bad: very expensive!  Sake is very expensive. Hamachi is very expensive. No it is not ok to use canned tuna fish to make a spicy tuna handroll. (I swear that is true. Canned tuna in $6.50 hand roll)  No cilantro DOES NOT go well with raw fish becasue raw cilantro has a very strong flavor and dominates the palette.  If you want good sushi overall then pass this place by. If you want to bask in the pseudo-fashonista world that of the uber superficial hipster then try it. I for one like good food. Community style seating and mismatched flavors do not make bad food taste better
Best sushi in NYC. Have been coming here for 3 years from Manhattan. Try the sushi bombs and the appetizers for something different and unique. So good. 👌👌👌

We came in around 3:30. Just before their recess. Place is dimly lit with community style seating. The waitress a was great, kind and very helpful. Service is excellent. Food delicious. The pork ramen; delectable! The noodles were perfect. For sushi; the A-B Crunch and the Oyako, omg it melted in our mouths. The place made us feel very relaxed. We are definitely coming back again!!
Go here. There are no words.

Delicioussssss. I can't tell you what to eat because everything is good there- sushi, pork belly(must eat), dumplings, etc. Eat them all. Momo Sushi Shack food, staffs and ambience are super super good. Thumps up.

Picked up a spicy tuna roll to go for $6.50. The six pieces were tiny and the quality did not make up for the small portion. On two pieces only half the seaweed was covered with rice! Very disappointed (and still hungry)
Delicious sushi and friendly staff. This place is cozy and the staff makes you feel welcomed. The sushi is delicious and service is great. Not a bad thing to say about this place.

My favorite restaurant. I could eat their inventive rolls and fresh fish for days. They even created their own format of roll here- the "bomb"! It's basically a half scoop of rice with the roll built on top- yes it's da bomb!- go for the party bomb platter ($19). But that's not all- their whole menu shines. Best on the menu include: pork Betty, tofu salad, kinpira, karaage, and seasonal tempura! Also, all of their specials are fresh and delicious. #1 rule when coming here: share everything!!! #2 rule: bring cash.

Momo Sushi Shack it's one of my favorite sushi places of all NYC, the food selection is refined and has some true pearls, the place is unique and the service is super friendly and professional, love it!

Wanted to try the sushi here. Service was great. Ordered the party bomb, fried chicken, dragon rolls karage roll, pork belly, and tuna tar tar. Sushi did not taste special. The dragon roll was $5 more just for using avocado instead of cucumber. Pork belly was great. Only one bathroom available but it was clean. Street parking was easy to find. Cash only.
Food is tasty but tolls are smaller than expected so order quite a few. Waiter recommended 3 rooms per person and I would agree after seeing the sizes. Also its cash only!!
Best sushis, best boss! Very cute place with a Bob in a heart!
The food was good. A lot of variety. The seaweed salad was yummy. The sushi portion was a little small.

Great food and great ambience at a not so hefty price level (at least compared to sushi prices at other fine sushi restaurants). As long as your ok with communal tables, and editing for your table during peak hours (you can hang out at a bar next door), your bound to have a great meal.
Delicious! Bombs are cute. Cash only though blahh

Momo is Amazing!!!! Love the food, ambiance, service... Really this is 5 stars on all counts...  I'm just a hungry girl without a fat wallet so for me I wish there was a filling/affordable lunch special or something.... maybe 1 day a week where i can pig out here...
Had take out. Great quality sushi. Small portions, and somewhat exspensive.
Good food, unfortunately very small portions. Disappointed by no appetizers and bring cash CC not accepted.
Food is TOP quality, place is nice, small and warm. Service was perfect: never had to call the waiter, who was often checking if we needed anything. Prices are fair, 25$ for a great dinner!
Sushi here was amazing. The pork belly was very delicious too. Would definitely recommend checking this place out although it is a little on the expensive side but worth it!
(Translated by Google) Delicious 👌  (Original) Delicioso 👌

They have an amazing Sushi, for a very -close to funny- low price. I never really understood why some places over price their sushi, which, from what i know, suppose to be a simple food. So why pay more? Oh, and do not miss the tuna tartar :)

What makes a restaurant more than the food is the service. Phillip Gilmour, the man behind it all, along with the rest of his staff made it shine.  Its awesome to see people with passion in what they do and mr. Gilmour oozes it.  His staff was all very knowledgeable and friendly as well.  I was pleasantly surprised when I called to make reservations that the only way to make a reservation was to sign up for the tasting menu starting at $65 a head.  For being in New York, having tasted what we did, compared to other tasting restaurants I've been to, the price is reasonable. With the tasting menu, they cater to your appetite and your pallet making the most of the $65 tasting whether your looking to get more full or to taste some more refined and yes smaller plates.   We enjoyed dishes ranging from pickled vegetables to fried prawns flown in live from Alaska.  Apparently Thursday nights are the best as they are always receiving shipments of a variety of fresh new product from all over the world.  I will definitely be back again!
Excellent food
It's good

Average sushi - I've had better at less hip places.  The canned responses to my questions from the waiter were not quite as clever as he thought they were, and instead he came off indifferent and condescending.  I went with a big group and couldn't hear anyone because of the rows of long tables and loud music. There seems to be a "cool" factor at play here I guess because the place is semi hard to find, which makes it feel like being in on a secret when you're inside.

My friend took me here for lunch, and I am blown away that stellar restaurants exist in Bushwick now!  YUM  Must order: the Pork Betty - pork belly (half pork half tender fat) with a small dime of mayo on top (order the fresh boiled farm egg with it!) in a bed of savory light sauce. 4 savory filling pieces, $10  Party bomb - the party bomb is all 4 variations of sushi - eel, spicy crunchy tuna, tuna and avocado, and salmon-  x 3 pieces each = 12 pieces, $19. The accompanying sauce is nice too! 3 soy sauces. 1 soy sauce, 1 blended soy sauce + light wasabi, 1 blended soy sauce + heavy wasabi.  The space is Super Cute! Professional, sophisticated, and our staff was very nice and attentive. Will definitely bring friends visiting new york to this location - a reason to bring newbies to explore Bushwick!
Awesome. So delicious. Worth the wait. Try the bomb rolls.
Insane quality and price. Actually good hot sake.  Party bomb order is a must,  as is the tuna tartare with quail egg... And the salmon herb... And more sake... And uni... And other stuff

Seems like a shack on the outside maybe but the inside is beautiful and clean. The food is delicious and beautifully presented! My mom, sis, and I came at an off-hour (around 4pm on a Saturday) and were the only ones there. The servers basically treated us like royalty and the food came out literally in minutes. Like many people say, you HAVE to try the pork belly. But everything I had there was good and unique! Pretty typical to slightly high sushi prices but since they're dishes are all extra special it's well worth the price.

Pretty cool boutique sushi joint. I found the food to be worth the price ($8ish/roll) that I paid but my friends said that the prices were "city prices". I often get specialty rolls back home at $13ish so it seemed pretty on par considering the rent in Brooklyn is probably way higher than CO.

My friend was in town from OR and we decided to check it out. It was a Friday night, so  we had to put our names down and come back almost an hour later. I love the benches, makes it great for meeting your neighbors (if you're into that). Sushi didn't take too long, as well the seaweed salad. Prices were good, service good, sushi good. Would definitely come back on a slower night.
Fantastic sushi, very understated. Would go again

(Translated by Google) MOMO I discovered it 2 years ago, thanks to Google maps. I put sushi in search and I left MOMO. I went with my girlfriend (the 2 sushi lovers). Our reaction to trying the first course was the same "astonished face without words." Best sushi in NY !!! THANKS GOOGLE MAPS !!  (Original) MOMO lo descubrí hace 2 años, gracias a Google maps. Puse sushi en search y me salio MOMO. Fui con mi novia (los 2 amantes de sushi). Nuestra reacción al probar el primer plato fue la misma "cara de asombro sin palabras". Mejor sushi de NY!!!. GRACIAS GOOGLE MAPS!!

The cozy dimly lit cafeteria-style space with its warm wood and electric blue LED tea lights sets a unique ambiance.  The food doesn't conform to any trends either.  The hot niku dishes are takes on classic fare you can't easily find in the city.  The sashimi is fresh and delicate-- a perfect complement to the heavier dishes like the lamb gyoza or the pork belly.
Awesome sushi and super cool place. Not so expensive.

Don't be fooled by the casual, friendly, and welcoming atmosphere. The taste and quality of the food here is on par (if not better) than all the stuffy and pretentious Japanese restaurants in NYC (I love them too though).  I suggest you give your food preference to your server and have them curate a meal for you. They always get it right. They're also flexible in that they ask you how much you are looking to spend.
A really fun and inexpensive place to have dinner with friends. We’ve extolled the virtues of the sushi, but the Momo Salad shouldn’t be overlooked!

FINALLY this place has a beer and wine license! That aside, the sushi here sure beats the stuff you can pick up at neighboring Brooklyn Natural. If you're not sure what you want, let the knowledgeable owner decide for you — you won't be disappointed. The communal tables let you make friends with the people next to you or, if you prefer, just keep to yourself and enjoy a hamachi roll alone.  The only downside is the long wait times. So if you're stomach is rumbling find something faster.
